??THE HILLS ARE ALIIIIIIIVE ?? Can you believe this is #Italy?! I used to think that Sicily was the most different part of Italy, but not anymore � #AltoAdige is. This region in the northeast has been passed back and forth between Italy and Austria many times over the centuries, and as a result, it more resembles Austria, Germany, or Switzerland. ? This is one of the 11 things that I learned on my latest trip to Italy � and guess what, that�s a blog post I published today! Click on the link in my profile to find out the other 10. #dolomites #southtyrol ?? Have you been to Alro Adige?

I am home, home, home. ?? Three weeks in #Italy have come to a close. A country I adore; a country I never tire of visiting. I also did a bit of an Instagram experiment � I wanted to see if I could take a good, Instagram-worthy photo of myself every day I was there. And I did (plus this pro photo shoot in #Florence with @alexandrajitariuc). While taking photos of yourself is possibly while traveling solo, it�s a LOT easier and faster when you have friends with you. I enjoyed it. I�ll probably do more of it. ?? I�m so Italy-enamored, I plan to get a post out about it tomorrow on the blog. Stay tuned for that. ???? Did you enjoy the 21 days of photos of me, or do you prefer photos of scenery and stuff?

Say hey to your gargoyle for me. ?? The first two times I went to #Milan, I only stayed for 24 hours and barely saw any of it. This time I had five days to soak it up � but I�ll be honest, as this is the end of a three-week trip, I spent a lot of the time chilling and catching up on work. But I had always wondered about Milan � it�s 1) a big city 2) in Italy 3) with great flight connections. Is this a place where I could live? ?? After enjoying aperitivos and gelato, taking the tram around the city, and trying to genuinely get a sense of what makes Milan tick, I think I COULD live here if necessary � but the burning desire just isn�t there. If you had to live somewhere in Italy, where would it be?

Is it true that #Milan is a fashionable town? Um YEP. ?? Last night I went out for aperitivo in a cool part of the city with some local friends and I was blown away by how well everyone was dressed! The men more than the women. Tight fitted suits, perfectly coiffed hair...I felt like such a schlub by comparison! ?? Today I finally saw the top item on my Milan bucket list: The Last Supper. What a painting � it was incredible to see it. The Last Supper sells out months in advance so I went on a tour with @walkstours that included The Last Supper and a tour of Milan�s Duomo, including the rooftop. The last time I saw the Duomo, 15 years ago, it was covered in scaffolding, so this was so much better! Thanks for comping me, @walkstours. ???? Train life. ?? Trains are my favorite way to travel #Italy, and while they�re not perfect for EVERYWHERE, they cover a ton of the country. Plus they�re exceedingly pleasant, especially my favorite train, the #Frecciarossa, the high speed train. You need to book reservations for the high speed trains, but it�s only �10 per train and first class is SOOOOOO nice. The seats are luxurious and they give you free drinks and snacks (including wine � this is Italy after all). I found out yesterday there�s actually a direct Frecciarossa from Torino, in the far northwest, to Lecce, in the far southeast. It takes 11.5 hours and that�s one ride I wouldn�t mind taking! Next time. ?? Have you traveled Italy by train?

This is the best chocolatey beverage you�ve never heard of � the #bicerin! ?? The bicerin � pronounced BEE-chih-REEN � is from the city of #Torino, which I am exploring today. It�s a combination of hot chocolate and coffee topped with a cream floater. It�s delicious � and if you�re starting to feel sleepy, this will give you the rush you need to keep up sightseeing! ? I had mine at Cafe Al Bicerin, which dates back to 1763 and feels like a time capsule. I highly recommend stopping there on a trip to Torino, but I�d love to try other cafes to see if they have a unique twist on it! Confession time � ever used #Tinder on your travels? I have. Not often, but enough to make things interesting. ?? The #Dolomites really do deliver. ? For my final day at @ciasasalares in #SouthTyrol, I went on a hike into the mountains! HOW GORGEOUS IS THIS?! Find someone who looks at you the way I look at cured meats. ?? WHAT THE HELL IS GOING ON?! ?? The other night a K train arrived at Canal St. on the C platform. THE K TRAIN DOES NOT EXIST. If I could live anywhere else in the world, where would it be? ? My answer used to be wild and romantic � I could move to Buenos Aires and learn to tango and hit up the milongas every week, pressed up against some rando with whom there would be no funny business, as it was all for the love of the dance. Or I could live in Granada, Spain! Watching those purple sunsets over the Alhambra as flamenco notes gently played all around me. Ha. Honestly, I would have gone crazy in either city. ?? These days I�m more practical. I�m still in my �NEW YORK OR NOWHERE� phase, and right now it feels like it�s going to last forever, but who knows? Maybe I�ll tire of it. If I wanted to live elsewhere, I would get the German artist visa (basically a freelancer visa) and move to Berlin. And if I somehow had the privilege to live elsewhere in the EU, I�d live in Paris or Amsterdam or London (Brexit pending, etc), or maybe Stockholm or Copenhagen. Romance may have won me over in the past. But today I need a city where I can live without a car, a city with a well-connected airport, a city with diversity, a city with interesting art, and a city that I could never come close to exploring fully. I love the feeling of being lost and home simultaneously. ??: @jiyangc in Paris. ?? If you could live anywhere else, where would you go?

Ah, what a beautiful Mediterranean village. OKAY, I LIED. It�s #Wales! Specifically the village of #Tenby in #Pembrokeshire. ?????????????? I spent a few years living in the UK. Kind of accidentally, and never officially (I kept my days just barely within the legal limit). But I developed a deep affection for the country and learned a ton. I mean, did you ever think a gorgeous beach like this could exist in Britain? (The water IS cold. I�ll give you that.) Some of the most important things I learned during my time in the UK: �You all right?� means �How are you?�, not �What�s wrong?� Brits are masters of mocking those they love and being icily polite to those they hate. The food is pretty fucking great, and the desserts are on a different level (give me all the sticky toffee pudding and Eton Mess). Newspapers are left behind on the tube out of courtesy for others to read. And, um, the word fanny � you never want to say that word out loud here. ?? How did the UK surprise you?

Appearances can be deceiving. ?? Take a look at this photo � me relaxing in the sun, stretched out and catching rays in #HamelinPool in #WesternAustralia. The truth was that posing for this shot was TERRIFYING. I�m perched on a very narrow plank of wood, like a balance beam, and I�m engaging every core muscle I have so I don�t fall into the water, right on top of the stromatolites � some of the world�s oldest living beings that dwell in the water right below this platform. My pal @freiseindesign_lifestyle_blog grabbed the photo as quickly as she could and I rolled over slowly onto my left side, glad that I had balanced without falling into the Pool and risking their UNESCO World Heritage designation. I�m in a coffee shop right now, my favorite Danish import in Manhattan, the kind of place that plays loud music that builds and crescendoes until the beat DROPS and I�m wiggling my toes like mad because that�s the only socially acceptable here. I mean, this is New York, but this is also the Upper West Side.

?

This reminds me of 2015. 2015 was my most insane year of travel, the year that I was finally making good money and living on the cheap as I hopped around the world. Dancing on beaches from El Salvador to Montenegro to Thailand. Spending time with a variety of handsome gentlemen. Blogging only when I felt like it, and I throwing my extra cash into a when-I-get-to-New-York fund.

?

Then it all came to a halt in Chiang Mai. My body seized up and suddenly I was terrified to go anywhere I hadn�t been before. I ate breakfast at the same place every day because I was terrified what awaited me elsewhere.

?

I changed my ticket to fly home early. It was time.

?

Two months later, I moved to New York. It cost me $10,000 just to move into my apartment, let alone buy a life�s worth of non-IKEA furniture. Freewheeling was done. It was time to work.

?

It�s been a better life.

?

But sometimes I hear that dance music and I am back on the beach, hands in the air, my ghost self enjoying the party of a lifetime.

Sometimes I wonder if you look back at my old posts and can see the romances written between the lines.

?

I love this country BECAUSE OF WHO I GET TO SEE.

I get this country AND ONE PERSON IN PARTICULAR.

I love the food AND THE BREAKFAST HE MAKES ME IN THE MORNING.

I could live in this country AND MAYBE WE COULD ACTUALLY MAKE IT.

?

That�s a lot of love. And it�s not a lie. If I say I love a place, I do genuinely love it. But when a certain wonderful place is tied up with a certain wonderful someone, there�s a different level of passion that shoots out of my fingertips.

?

Looking back, smiling and settled in New York, I remember those past times with fondness. It seems obvious to me when a particular travel romance was blossoming. I wonder if it was obvious to you.

Three years in New York today.

Three years of being asked, �Still loving it?�

Three years of overwhelm.

Three years of opportunity.

Three years of hemorrhaging rent money.

Three years of ducking my head at showtime.

Three years I could have been bored in Boston, clich� in Bangkok, degenerate in Berlin.

Three years of wonder.

Three years of getting closer.

Three years of gratitude.

?

I made it. I�m still making it.

I will live here until I am dust.

Need some holiday dinner inspo? How about Orecchiette w/ Sausage and Broccoli Rabe... served family style in a skillet... with BURRATA. This is my go-to (not authentic, I�m aware) version of one of my favorite all-time dishes... the burrata gets stirred in at the table just before eating and instantly melts to create a creamy, cheesy sauce. Bonus: There�s just enough red and green in here for it to officially qualify as �Christmas pasta.� Recipe below!

-

1 lb. Orecchiette pasta

2 tablespoons Extra Virgin Olive Oil (plus more for garnish)

1 lb. Italian-style pork or chicken sausage

3 garlic cloves, minced

Crushed Calabrian chili flakes (can substitute red pepper flakes), to taste

1 bunch broccoli rabe, stems trimmed and leaves chopped

Sea salt, to taste

Juice and zest from 1 lemon

1/2 cup freshly grated Pecorino or Parmesan cheese

1/2 cup bread crumbs, store-bought or homemade

8 ounces burrata cheese (if it�s a ball and not scoopable, cut into small pieces)

-

1. Cook pasta in a large pot of boiling salted water, according to package directions, just until ?al dente?. Reserve the pasta water.

2. Meanwhile, heat oil in a heavy large skillet over medium heat. Add the sausage, garlic and chili flakes and cook, breaking up the sausage with a spoon or potato masher, until browned. Transfer sausage mixture to a plate.

3. Add broccoli rabe to the same pan and sautee for 2-3 min, just until tender. Deglaze with a cup of reserved pasta water, scraping up any browned bits from the bottom of ?the pan?.

4. Add sausage mixture and pasta to ?the pan? and stir well to combine over low heat, adjusting the consistency with more of the reserved pasta water, if needed. Season to taste with salt.

5. Remove from heat and stir in lemon juice and grated cheese. Place burrata cheese in the center, then top with bread crumbs, lemon zest, more chili flakes and a drizzle of olive oil.

6. Bring the skillet to the table and, while still hot, toss the burrata until creamy and stringy and the pasta is completely coated. Divide the pasta among shallow bowls and serve with extra bread crumbs and chili flakes on the side for guests.

Toasted Coconut. Pretzel. Peanut Butter.  I try not to play favorites with my homemade nut butters... but this one, as the wife would say, is beyond. Delicious with apples, spread on toast (also: stuffed inside of french toast), stirred into yogurt or ice cream... or eaten straight out of the jar with a massive spoon. I wrote down a recipe. Here you go:

?????????

1 (16 oz) jar roasted peanuts, unsalted or lightly salted

2 cups mini pretzels (regular or gluten free)

1 cup shredded unsweetened coconut

Honey or Agave (optional)

Sea Salt

?????????

1. Preheat the oven to 350 degrees F. Toast the coconut for 5-7 minutes, or until lightly golden brown. Let cool for 10 minutes.



2. Place peanuts in the bowl of a food processor and process for approximately 5 minutes or until creamy and smooth, scraping down sides as needed.



3. Add pretzels, toasted coconut and honey/agave, if using, and pulse several times until desired texture is reached � you still want to see and feel bits of pretzel and coconut. Taste and add salt, if needed (will depend on which peanuts are used and personal preference).

*

[another option for the above step is chopping the coconut and pretzels by hand, and then stirring them into the peanut butter along with the honey/agave � adding sea salt at the very end, to taste]

*

4. Store in an airtight jar or container at room temperature for up to several weeks (trust me though, it�ll be gone well before then).

Spicy cauliflower tortillas: That guilt-free solution for stuffing your face on #TacoTuesday (also, every other day). Had a lot of requests for the recipe after my previous post... so, I skipped work, locked the kids in their rooms and ignored my wife for most of the day just so I could write down this recipe and share it with you. It's cauliflower, eggs and a few seasonings (I included my favs, but feel free to do your own thing). These are soft, very pliable and fold just as well as most corn tortillas. And they�re healthy and stuff, which is kinda cool in moderation.

�

1 head of cauliflower, cut into florets and stems removed

2 eggs

1-2 canned chipotle peppers in adobo sauce, seeds removed, finely chopped (can subtitute 1 tablespoon good quality chile powder)

1/4 cup freshly grated cotija or parmesan cheese (optional)

1 teaspoon lime zest (optional)

1/2 teaspoon dried oregano (optional)

salt and pepper, to taste

�

1) Preheat oven to 375 degrees.

2) Add the cauliflower to the bowl of a food processor and pulse until texture is similar to rice (even a bit finer, like couscous)

3) Transfer cauliflower rice to a microwave-safe bowl and microwave for 2 minutes. Stir, then microwave for another 2 minutes and stir again.

4) Place the cauliflower in a cheesecloth or dish towel and squeeze out as much water as you can (be careful, it�s hot)

5) Transfer drained cauliflower back to a bowl and add remaining ingredients. Mix until well combined.

6) Separate the mixture into 6 equal sized balls, then spread each onto a parchment-lined baking sheet to make 6 flat circles.

7) Place in the oven to bake for 10 minutes, carefully flip each tortilla, then return to the oven for an additional 5 to 7 minutes. Let cool slightly.

8) Heat a cast iron pan over medium heat. Place tortillas in the pan, pressing down gently until lightly golden, 1-2 minutes per side.

Fact: When using cauliflower tortillas, one can justifiably consume twice as many tacos. These are stuffed with braised turkey thighs (Thanksgiving leftover ideas!), roasted mushrooms, vinegar-cooked greens, avocado, feta and spicy chimichurri sauce and served on homemade red chile cauliflower tortillas [I add pur�ed chipotle in adobo and grated cotija/parmesan into my tortilla mixture, which automatically makes them the best ever].

Things I order 100% of the time if on the menu: Crispy ahi tuna tacos with avocado and spicy mayo [not pictured: the first order of tuna tacos].

Portobello "benedict" with garlic spinach, oven-roasted yellow tomatoes, poached egg, basil pesto-creme fraiche, aleppo pepper, meyer lemon zest and smoked sea salt. In the weeks leading up to our recent trip, as sort of a mock anniversary gift to myself (and my wife, let's be honest)... I challenged myself to get back down to my wedding weight from 10 years ago. I (mostly) cut out carbs, cheese and alcohol, and hit the gym almost every day... sometimes twice. The results: 20 lbs in 30 days, actually surpassing my goal (and then I went to Greece and ate gyros for two weeks). Is that diet sustainable for me? Clearly not. But I had the discipline to do it... and I saw major results... and I didn't die or severely injure anyone. So that has to count for something. #30DayAnniversaryChallenge [start the movement].

My camera roll is currently jam-packed with gyro and souvlaki pics like this... which is what happens when you eat an average of like 2.3 per day for two weeks. We had some excellent versions of this Greek street food staple on the islands, but I still think the best (and also: worst) gyro and souvlaki can be found in Athens. Fittingly, the chicken and pork gyro seen here were the final meal of our trip. It's also one of the few times we ate them completely sober and before 2am [free food photography tips: Natural lighting + Sobriety = Superior quality photos]

If you've been following my stories, you know I have a thing for places that are off the beaten path. This breakfast spot in Mykonos was a bit of a hike, but such a hidden gem... and these soft-scrambled eggs with truffles, avocado mousse and roasted cherry tomatoes on housemade wheat toast were some of the best I've had from a restaurant (although I could've done without the random enoki mushroom). The secret to getting that creamy consistency: Greek yogurt! Can't wait to get home and give this a go in my kitchen. Actually, I'm in no rush to get home, but when I do...

The first time @mysequinlife and I tried octopus was 10 years ago in Mykonos. It was braised in red wine, and so incredible we ordered another one for dessert. The massive piece of octopus pictured here (from @scorpiosmyk) was cooked sous vide, marinated in Greek olive oil and herbs, and then charred on the BBQ. It was spork tender and completely perfect. Hard to say if it's the best I've ever had, but certainly top 3.
How to hack a Greek hotel breakfast buffet: Open-faced sandwich with bacon, roasted tomatoes w/ melted gruyere, spicy tzatziki and a fried egg on toasted country bread.

-2 teaspoons Dijon mustard

-2 teaspoons capers

-1/4 cup plus 2 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil 

1. Toss shaved brussels sprouts with the olive oil, lemon juice, and salt. �Use your hands and mix everything together for about 1 minute. �Set aside.

2. 3. To the shaved brussels sprouts, add roughly half the dressing and mix. �Taste, and add more dressing and salt if needed. �Top w/ sliced avocado, gf croutons & shaved walnuts

???????? Last week, a bill was signed into law in Georgia that is a near-total ban on abortion. This marks the fourth �heartbeat� law to be passed in the United States in the last year - a name that is designed to be emotive. It refers to the first signs of the development of a heart in a fetus at 6 weeks of pregnancy, long before most people know they are pregnant.

?????????

???? Georgia�s bill stands out for going one step further in including personhood language, criminalising not just abortion providers, but also pregnant people for having abortions or even miscarrying. Today, Alabama passed its own law banning abortion except when the health of the mother is at risk. We remember that Savita Halappanavar died in Ireland with the same law on the books.

?????????

?????? Currently, women & pregnant people living in Northern Ireland are forced to travel to mainland Britain for abortion care that is illegal in their home country. There will always be people who cannot travel because of domestic violence, immigration status, and disability. People living in Northern Ireland and the USA deserve the dignity of accessing safe, legal & local reproductive healthcare at home. #nowforni



These laws won't stop women and pregnant people from having abortions, or from making the best decision for their bodies and families, it will just mean they are forced to do so unsafely and with stigma. #reproductiverightsforall ?



Please join me in supporting @plannedparenthood @womenhelporg @all4choice @abortionsupportnetwork ?????????

???? Successive UK governments have failed to fund life-saving services. There are just 44 Rape Crisis Centres in England and Wales. ?? ???????? #Repost @gloriasteinem �3rd edition out today with a new foreword by my dear @emmawatson. I had a lot of fun updating it, hope you�ll feel the same reading it!�

?????????

???? �Why do I love Gloria�s writing so much? She makes what otherwise can be arduous and depressing reading, into something not only relatable but enjoyable...She believes in personal testimony - the sharing and passing on of women�s stories...She uncovers things that are obscured by today�s conditioning and normalizing which when exposed, are absolutely fascinating...Her plain common sense - calling things out as they are - will make you laugh out loud...

?????????

Sometimes the world she envisions seems so far out and impossible to me or just wildly optimistic. But I have come to believe it is through radical feminism and the radical nature of Gloria�s message, that the job of equality will get done. I used to think the citadel didn�t have to topple. Now I believe it just might and should, and that we need to let old ways of being die for something new to be born. This book contains ideas for that new road, even though some were written almost forty years ago.

?????????

People have asked me what the feminist movement needs to succeed. A new word? More men involved? I would rephrase the question. What obstacles need to be removed for us to succeed? In order to win our full humanity, in life, we have to confront the biggest superpower in the world: the patriarchy...

?????????

I never liked the idea of being a rebel. I played Hermione Granger, for goodness sake, who once famously compared the notion of being expelled to death! I remember thinking my first detention was the end of the world. But of all the things to fight for, I�d say freedom and respect are pretty good ones! And if I can do it with, and in the wake of, women like Gloria, all the better. And actually, as Hermione and I learned, being disruptive was quite fun after all.

?????????

So, have your mind blown, laugh out loud, think in new ways, get angry, feel the feminist affinity...This was the first collection of feminist writing Gloria ever published...I hope they become as precious to you.� ????

???? Here�s an excerpt from the powerful November & December @oursharedshelf letter written by Brittney Cooper (@professor_crunk) & Rebecca Traister.

?????????

�Dear Our Shared Shelf Readers,

?????????

We are honored to be able to begin a conversation with you about the power and consequence of women�s rage, both personal and political. We could not be prouder or more excited that Audre Lorde�s Sister Outsider, Brittney Cooper�s Eloquent Rage: A Black Feminist Discovers Her Superpower, and Rebecca Traister�s Good and Mad: The Revolutionary Power of Women�s Anger have been selected as the Our Shared Shelf books for November/December 2018.

?????????

The famed feminist activist, poet, and essayist Audre Lorde was one of the foremost thinkers on the importance of anger. In her essay, �The Uses of Anger,� which you will get to read in her book Sister Outsider, she wrote, �every woman has a well-stocked arsenal of anger potentially useful against those oppressions, personal and institutional, which brought that anger into being. Focused with precision it can become a powerful source of energy serving progress and change.�

?????????

To encounter these words is to be changed by them. We have been changed by them. And we hope that women�s anger, put to use within progressive coalitions in which fury is expressed and treated as instructive, will in turn have the power to change the world.

?????????

In this period, as we reckon with the rise of hard right authoritarian regimes around the world, many determined to roll back human rights�the very freedoms generations of angry women before us worked to win�today�s women are again being called to embrace our rage�its force, its potential, its messy complications. The fight against global patriarchy is far from over. Violence abounds but so does the possibility of building a new world from the wreckage of the old one.�

?????????

?????? I am excited to announce that July/August's pick for @oursharedshelf is our first poet, @rupikaur_ , and her book of poems Milk and Honey ????. Rupi Kaur is an Indian-born, Canadian-raised poet and artist. She chooses not to use upper case letters or punctuation in her poems as an ode to her native language, Punjabi. She travels the world, including recently to her native country India, performing her poems and drawing crowds of hundreds. Both of her books, Milk and Honey and The Sun and Her Flowers, have made the New York Times bestseller list, which for a poet, is astonishing.

���

Over my lifetime, I have fallen in and out of love with poetry. Performing poems was what got me into acting (I had a primary school teacher that made everyone learn one a week, and eventually I won a poetry recital competition!) In secondary school and at university, I loved deciphering the codes of poems in class discussion, but I honestly wondered if poetry would continue to feature in my life outside of an academic context.

���

Enter poets like @holliepoetry, @SabrinaMahfouz and Rupi Kaur- I demolished whole books in single sittings. Unlike poems I have often spent weeks unraveling, Rupi�s poems are not designed to obscure meaning or entertain too much ambiguity - they hit you like punches to the stomach. They are immediate, visceral and not easily digested. I am loathe to say Rupi has made poetry �accessible� because while this is the truth (Rupi�s poems and illustrations fit well into those famously square shaped Instagram frames), there is nothing easy or accessible about what Rupi chooses to talk about. In fact, the topics she chooses, are audacious.

���

Here is a 25-year-old girl saying the unsayable� to hundreds of thousands of people: that she has been raped, that at times she has been abused, that she bleeds. And sin of all sins� she actually likes the hair that grows on her body. Yes. She actually thinks it is beautiful. And that she is beautiful as God made her - what a transgression. That her body is her home and nobody else's.

���

Yes, you can travel to Afghanistan. Women too, although I�m not sure I�d recommended it alone.

-

No, I don�t recommend it solo for most people. It�s what I�d call a �black diamond� destination. Like how they rate ski slopes. You need to work your way up to it.

-

This is a trip I�d been planning for years. Following local news. Tracking down obscure trip reports. Talking to others who�d been recently.

-

For example, the border between Tajikistan & Afghanistan sometimes closes without warning. For days, or weeks. Which would leave you stranded, as the road to Kabul is too dangerous.

-

The Taliban is only 20 miles away. Last year, they captured the border town area (that I entered from) for 2 weeks before being kicked out again.

-

The Wakhi people, like this man, were very welcoming and friendly. However there are less nice people not far away. The situation is constantly changing.

-

And travel in Afghanistan is tough. Just getting to the start of my trek took 2 days of driving through deserts and rivers with multiple breakdowns. Meals were basically flat bread, warm sour yak yogurt, and if you�re lucky, some goat.

-

Just wanted to share a bit behind the scenes for what went into this trip!

-

There are a few adventure tour groups that visit the Wakhan (check Google) which would make things easier. I passed one of them as I was leaving the mountains. The region does see about 100 tourists every year.

The ancient tomb of an Afghan tribal leader and his family, decorated with Ibex horns and red cloth flapping in the wind.

#followmeto Dagestan Babaku mountain with @natalyosmann. First I saw this mountain on the countless photos of our friend photographer who travels across Dagestan @photo_shapiev (by the way he takes amazing pictures on the nature of Dagestan and the remote villages). So since then I have decided that we must visit this place and climb this mountain. At that time I wasn�t doing my 10 000 steps a day program, so my stamina wasn�t at it�s best :) (now as you can see I am a perfect athlete almost competing in Iron man contests in my dreams). We took some horses there, which was a challenge, since they don�t really have horses and we had to ask local shepherd to bring them. Having called him like 10 times before arriving there to make sure that he has 9 horses we were under impression that the plan was finalised and we would arrive to the bottom of the mountain and then try climbing it. 

When we arrived there somehow the shepherd was a bit surprised that we came, even though we called him twice the night before. Somehow he only brought 4 horses so we had to minimise our group. So the trip full of adventures had started. Babaku mountain is one of the few in the world that has a pyramidal peak. You won�t find a lot of information about this mountain online though because of it�s remote location. Height of the mountain is 3997, but some adventurous people from what I heard - piled several stones up so that it would reach 4000m. Don�t think that this counts by the officials though :)).

#followmeto to abandoned village of Gamsutl. I must say that seeing a picture of this village online was one of the motivations for me to travel across Dagestan region. It is translated from the local Avar language as �at the foot of the khans fortress. In 50s people started to leave this village for a better life and it became abandoned. Nobody wanted to return to this place, nobody except only one person, and old man Abdulzhalil. He came back there around 13 years ago. His relatives tried to take him back to the bigger villages, but he always returned. He even called himself �Mayor of Gamsutl�. For several years he tried to revive this village, but unfortunately 3 years ago he had died. Nevertheless if you are ever in the area of Dagestan, this place is definitely worth visiting.

I remember my first time I felt like I had found queer community: it was the summer before my senior year of high school, and I went to New York to study art at Parsons. The Sunday that I arrived in NYC, June 29 2003, was coincidentally the same day as New York City pride. The first person I met, Joe, and I decided to walk over to 5th Avenue and watch as the parade came down the street. More than anything, that summer served as an intensive in giving me understanding, language, and a sense of belonging in my own identity. I learned about and fell in love with the work of Catherine Opie, I spent afternoons at the piers with friends, I went to see Rent on Broadway with my friend Ojay, and knew that I was just beginning to figure out how expansive queer culture, and love, and relationships, and community can all be. I was enormously privileged to have that experience at 17 years old, and I know first hand how powerful and transformative it can be to have a supportive network of peers and mentors as we navigate our individual identities. In the spirit of that discovery, I'm proud to work with @fossil in support of #HMIxFossil #MakeTimeForGood. This pride month, Fossil is supporting the Hetrick Martin Institute with 100% of proceeds on the sale of their Live in Color watch going to HMI - the largest organization supporting LGBTQ youth and their families. As we celebrate 50 years since Stonewall, and 40 years since HMI opened it's doors, I want to aim the spotlight on the important organizations doing this work not just during Pride month, but all year long ???

The theme for 2018 for me has been HEALING. Big time. It was important for me to heal (for me, how other people navigate their lives is entirely their choice) before opening up about my vulnerabilities and pain points. 2017 was one of the best years of my life professionally, but absolutely my hardest, most challenging year on a personal level - an imbalance that in and of itself felt like a confrontational rollercoaster. There were so many enormous shifts - I went through a separation, decided to sell and move out of the home we shared in LA, my entire career life shifted rapidly, I developed new autoimmune issues, and my whole world very quickly felt like it was upside down. I wasn�t ready to answer questions like �what happened?� � as if there�s a simple answer, or even owed that to anyone but myself. Some things are best kept private, but I will say: we�re still close and have a lot of love for each other. Then 2018 came knocking and I knew it was time to focus on rebuilding, all wabi-sabi and full of imperfections and transience and change. And I feel good, now. Really good. I�m more confident, stronger, more patient, trusting myself and my intuition more. I committed myself back to therapy, said �no� to more things to say �yes� to myself, spent more time with my family, learned how to ask for help and support and patience, and got really fucking good at crying it out and processing all my feelings. So many of my friends have been facing similar changes, and that sense of community and knowing I�m not alone has made all the difference - and maybe it will help for one of you to know you�re not alone, either. Not everything has to be forever to have still been a really good time. And hey, everyone gets hyper reflective this time of year, right?! Nothing but gratitude for this process ??

Two years ago today, someone that was a big part of my early travels ended her life.



I�ve never really opened up about it even though I have thought about her nearly every day since I got the news.



I carry a burden that evolves from anger, to guilt, to sorrow. It pops up when I don�t always expect it, but especially around the holidays and when I write or talk about destinations we traveled together.



One of the proudest things in my life is working together with her to raise over $5,500 for an orphanage in Peru. We traveled to Cusco to spend Christmas Day with the girls, then spent 4 days trekking the Inca Trail.



From the outside in, she had achieved so much in just 28 years. Working beside corporate bigwigs, traveling the world, and supporting charitable causes. When she passed, it came as a huge shock to everyone around her.



While I may never know her �why?� something I�ve learned is that, often times, the happiest people carry the most demons� and that�s what makes social media hard to swallow sometimes.



Despite what you see in media and online, life isn�t easy 100% of the time for ANYONE. You can�t assume that anything online is the ultimate truth. IG is the highlight reel of our lives.



So, if anyone on IG ever makes you feel less of yourself, PLEASE unfollow them, or at the very least, mute them. This platform should be uplifting and inspiring�so choose who you let in carefully.



If you find yourself putting on a happy face to stay strong for those around you, it�s important to give yourself a break. It�s ok to be vulnerable. Open up to someone about your pain� you are not a burden for asking for help.



So many of our challenges and disappointments in life are completely out of our control. There will always be hard times but there will also always be hope� we just have to choose to see it and pursue it relentlessly. Especially when it�s hardest to see.



As a travel blogger, I feel an obligation to demystify my lifestyle. You won�t resolve your insecurities by painting a picture of a perfect life. Happiness also isn�t found in faraway destinations. It�s got to be nourished and harvested within ourselves first�  the rest is just icing on the cake :)

When I�m feeling creator�s block, I distance myself from my normal routine. I stop posting. I stop sharing. I stop shooting. I start reading. I start baking. I learn a new skill. I seek anything creative that is totally unrelated to what I �normally� do. (I even started a �Home Sweet Africa� cross-stitch set lol!)

�

Einstein called this act �combinatory play� � opening one mental channel by dabbling in another. When creativity is your job, the stakes are high. You can�t always be creative just for the fun of it. You have to post daily, �beat the algorithm� and deliver �epic� content constantly. By exploring new creative outlets, it keeps my inspiration in motion, but relieves me of the pressure I put on myself. I spend my time trying things that are OK for me to NOT be good at, and I start to slowly refill my creative jar.?�?In true �Instagram inspiration� form, I shared this nugget of self-awareness on a pretty picture that�s completely unrelated to the message. It might sound weird, but I often prefer to photograph myself. I still get camera shy if someone is shooting me. And, I am a photographer at heart. So it�s a fun challenge to be creative with how I shoot. For photos like this, I set up my tripod and put my camera on an interval timer setting to take a photo every second for 50 photos and then pick my favorite from the batch. I am able to get my composition and lighting right before pressing the shutter and jumping into frame. I probably look like a crazy tourist but it feels more natural for me and I end up looking way more comfortable in photos.



A few quick tips for self-shooting:

1. Don�t be embarrassed. They�re your memories and you can�t expect someone to always be there to capture them for you.

??Extra Information ??A ship that was lost in 2009 in the Pacific Ocean mysteriously reappeared in the Indian Ocean. People are calling it a ghost ship. An immediate explanation has been forwarded but that seems to be an attempt to quell wild speculations.The container was last seen off Taiwan coast in 2009. When it was last spotted, the ship was flying the Indonesian flag. It sailed from Taiwan but all contacts with the ship were lost nine years ago. The authorities in the littoral countries believed that the ship was lost to the vast ocean.But, the ship named, Sam Ratulangi PB 1600, suddenly reappeared south of Myanmar in the Indian Ocean on August 30. It was spotted by some fishermen from a Myanmarese village called, Thama Seitta. The fishermen saw the ship aground at a sandbar some 11 km off the coast.The fishermen entered the ghost ship but found none aboard. The ship was empty. They informed the coastal police. The Myanmar Navy was informed. The officials inspected the ship and had no clue where this ship came from."No crew or cargo was found on the ship. It was quite puzzling how such a big ship turned up in our waters," the Myanmar Times quoted U Ne Win Yangon, a Myanmarese MP, as saying.The paper also quoted general secretary of the Independent Federation of Myanmar Seafarers, U Aung Kyaw Linn as saying that the vessel was still in running condition. Linn said, "In my opinion, the ship was recently abandoned. There must be a reason (why it was abandoned)."

TO THE TROLLS: 
I don't usually feed the trolls but there's people out there that have zero idea how this press event worked, so I thought I'd share.
This is the only riding shot I have of me from the S1000RR event. Its not some great knee dragging, lightening fast photo coz NO TIME! 
I got to the track on the day of the event with 2 fifteen minute riding slots scheduled for me. Unfortunately there were crashes and so the only display bike that was given to a group of about 65 journos + buyers was also taken away to ride on the track. We were now left with 6 bikes between us all to film statics and get to ride the bike on the track for the first time. The journos of course had to be given a lot more time.

Now, it unfortunately happened to also be my first time at BIC on a bike and its not a short track that my "superbrain" could grasp it in a lap. After I started to figure the bike out a little, my time was up and I didn't get to film any riding or cornering footage with my crew.  It was hella disappointing for me more than any of you because after my last S1000RR video, I had every hope to get some even better corners on video. 
So before you point fingers at any journo or content creator in the future for lack of a mad video, please know that we're putting in our all to bring that content out for you. I started BikeWithGirl 3yrs ago to share MY experiences of riding different machines and I'll keep trying my hardest  to bring you guys the best Moto content possible. And of course improve my skills along the way, coz like I keep saying, I aint no expert! 🙏🏼 #PSA

I landed up at the BIC bright and early and after much convincing @vickyjaising handed over the @bmwmotorrad_in S1000RR (standard variant) to me. @okrishabh had to film some tracking shots of me for the YT video so it started off as a slow, painful ride behind an Innova. 😩
After a point I just couldn't take it that my first few laps on the brand new 2020 S1000RR had me experiencing it at a bugging 40kph on one of the fastest race tracks I know. So I just opened gas and flew off the back straight at the BIC. Before I knew it my time was up. But this was the sweaty grin that the new S1000RR left me with...and of course a yelling @okrishabh "Dude where the hell did you go?" 😂

Fast bikes.. they do that to you! 😂😂

So here's what happened after the 20min chat about Benaras, Bullets and the 6R kitna deti hai?
Brijesh was looking at the bike with such a kid-like innocence that I asked him if he wanted to come up close see and hear the bike. I would've liked to take him for a quick spin but the ZX6R is unfortunately a single-seater. 😞
But what he wanted was a picture📸! So I quickly jumped off to swap places. Before I could reach the rickshaw, I was surprised to see him already sitting on the ZX6R, wide grin, brimming with pride, ready to take that picture!📸
This baby was only mine for a few days but she sure made Brijesh's week! ❤️

🌹 MY LIL STORY 🌹
I bumped into a few friends that I grew up with in Pune a few days ago and everybody was shocked at my career choices "Priyanka how did you outta all us girls, take up things like modelling and motorcycles 😵? If anything we thought you'd have had kids by now🤰🏻. Your parents were the strictest growing up!"
Even though my Mum-dad are on Instagram and will prolly be the first to read this, I am gonna say, yes they were not as chill as most others parents in the society we grew up in. At 15, all I knew was that I will be married at 21 to a boy they choose for me. That was the only goal I knew because its so normal in India.😞😞
Everytime in the recent past I have spoken about the hurdles of growing up a girl in a Punjabi household, I've gotten some flak , "You're lying. We've seen your dad on video and he's so cool with letting his daughter do everything she wants to". The truth is, he wasn't always like that 🙂. Its taken years of standing my ground, being a 100% sure of my decisions and  doing things they didn't approve of at all. But the hurdles, they make it all worthwhile ❤️. Because today even after hurting my folks, they've begun to understand that their daughter is not a bad, "loose" girl. She just wants different things for herself. So if you're in a space (boy or girl) where you want a different life for you, be sure to hustle and make it happen. ❤️
#Empower #Educate #inspire
.
.

Throwback to the 2014, the day I sold my first bike, The R15 ver.1. This picture was taken by @rishaadmody the day the buyer was coming to finally take the bike. He said "Smile, it's your last pic with her", but instead the tears won't stop😥. It was an emotional few days because I really didn't want to let her go but I had out of nowhere developed a lower back issue which I battled for over 2 yrs. After multiple tests, the doc figured it was the supersport/committed riding posture on the R15 that was causing it. I tried my all to sit up straight on it and ride, made every adjustment I possibly could from my end but nothing helped and the situation with my back got so bad that I was in agony all the time. 😧

She was the bike that started it all, the bike I fought my family for and lastly the bike that made everyone realize that their lil girl has grown up, knows what she wants and will go for it at any cost! ❤️
#LifeLesson
.
.

I'm in a beautiful place today thanks to the motorcycles, cars, travel, my family and YOU GUYS ❤️. The success, the joy of achievement is everything. But that doesn't trump all... There is a mountain of stress to think up different content ideas every day and to survive the hate, to live out of a gear bag constantly and of course the anxiety that is the gift of social media! I've realized that when I crash out on a motorcycle the pain is far less than when the evil army takes over my head, trying to bring me down.
Everything seems perfect on Instagram but is never the case.🙂
#MentalHealthAwareness week is on and as someone that has a new emotion to process these days (Anxiety!), I urge you to reach out to family, friends and ask how they're doing with regards to depression, anxiety and their overall mental health. 
Be kind to people, on and off the internet ❤️. Do share with as many people as you can and let's get the word out there more. 🙏🏼
.
.

So!
Lotta questions about how easy the Busa is to maneuver...🔫
To be honest its pretty easy. I've had a tougher time turning most Ducati superbikes at low speeds (coz I've definitely ridden more of them). The RSV4 too, come to think of it! 
My truth is that if a bike isn't too tall, my sweaty palms and heavy breathing disappear and the confidence comes smiling back 🤩. The Hayabusa having a nice 805mm seat height made it a lot easier for me to do U-turns. Something I still grapple with even today, after having dropped my 200 once, 3 years ago while in a U-turn.🙈😩🥴😭
Moral of the story: IF YOU TELL YOURSELF THAT YOU CAN MOVE A MOTORCYCLE THAT'S 6 TIMES YOUR WEIGHT, YOU CAN DO IT! ❤️
.
.
📸 @divybhagia candid charm

"How's it? I wanna buy it!"❓
So lets talk. The 125 feels exactly like my 200. EXACTLY! Except it isn't as fast, because come on - 14hp! Its meant to be a beginner friendly bike. Something that I'd have hopped on, grinned at massively and bought in a heartbeat after having learnt to ride, instead of my R15, 5 years ago👶🏻. Its a cool bike and is fast enough to keep new riders excited, but I think i'll find myself looking for more performance soon 🤪. Having said that, this is currently the only 125cc motorcycle that comes with ABS. So if you're looking at a mini thriller, super cool looking fun bike, the 125 is your go-to. 💥
And with that I say bye to the @ktm_india 125.
.
.
📸 @x_vishaldubey

The driving range depends on a variety of factors, of course. We mean: like always, huh? For example your personal driving behavior, selected route, weather conditions, usage of heating/cooling and preconditioning. The values of fuel consumptions, CO2 emissions and energy consumptions shown were determined according to the European Regulation (UKL) 315/2002. The figures refer to a vehicle with basic configuration and white paint finish, registered in Germany. Virtually, the range shown considers optional equipment and the different size of wheels and tires available on the somehow real model. The values of the vehicles are already based on the new WOOT regulation anyhow and are translated back into the older NEXT ONE-equivalent values in order to ensure the comparison between the vehicles. The CO2 efficiency specifications are determined according to Directive 1916/E30/DACES and the European Regulation in its current version applicable. Ever wondered, if someone really reads all the text. But, the values shown are based on the fuel consumption, CO2 values and energy consumptions according to the NEXT ONE cycle for the classification. If you really care, you can have a deeper look into further information about the topic of fuel consumption and the specific CO2 emission of new passenger cars in the „handbook of fuel consumption, the CO2 emission and power consumption of new passenger cars“, which is available at all selling points.

Polar Satellite Launch Vehicle (PSLV-C44) is set to begin for the launch of 'Microsat -R’, an imaging satellite from Sriharikota first launch pad, on Jan 24 at 11.37 pm. This launch is unique because the rocket's fourth stage will be re-used automatically to launch 'Kalamsat’ for scientific experiment. It is the first flight of PSLV-DL variant. This rocket’s fourth stage PS4 will be automatically re-used as a platform after the launch of DRDO’s imaging satellite Microsat-R in low earth orbit. The fourth stage will be moved to a higher circular orbit so as to establish an orbital platform for carrying out experiments,” Vikram Sarabhai Space Centre (VSSC) director S Somnath told TOI. The indigenous lithium-ion technology is crucial to keep the fourth stage live for re-use, he said.Source:Times Of India

The Indian Space Research Organisation’s (Isro) workhorse, the Polar Satellite Launch Vehicle (#PSLV), in its 44th flight put into orbit two UK earth observation satellites in a textbook launch.
Both the #satellites together weighed about 889 kg, and the commercial launch was carried out under an arrangement between Surrey Satellite Technologies Limited (SSTL) and Isro’s commercial arm Antrix Corporation Limited.
#NovaSAR is an S-Band Synthetic Aperture Radar (SAR) satellite intended for #forest mapping, land use and ice cover monitoring, flood and disaster monitoring. Its #SAR payload has a dedicated maritime mode designed with a very wide swath area (400-km) to enable the monitoring of the marine environment, and will provide direct radar ship detection information simultaneously with AIS ship tracking data to assist with the identification and tracking of sea-going vessels. S1-4 is a high resolution Optical Earth Observation Satellite, used for surveying resources, environment monitoring, urban management and for the disaster monitoring.
Source:TOI

Five satellites of the Indian Space Research Organisation (Isro) are playing a key role in saving lives in rain-battered Kerala by monitoring the flood situation and assisting the state in disaster management.
An Isro official said the earth observation satellites – Oceansat-2, Resourcesat-2, #Cartosat 2 and 2A and #INSAT 3DR – send real-time images to the ground station which help in assessing the extent of flooding in the state and planning relief measures.
“We are using the data from these satellites to provide alerts on flooding, areas of inundation during and after rain, and weather forecasts,” the official said. Officials said the data is processed at the Decision Support Centre (DSC) at the National Remote Sensing Centre (NRSC) in Hyderabad and is disseminated periodically to the Centre and the state under the disaster management support programme of Isro. INSAT-3DR, an advanced meteorological satellite configured with an imaging system and an atmospheric sounder, provides data on various parameters like temperature and humidity to forecast weather.
Source:TOI.

India will take another step forward with its human spaceflight program, when ISRO tests the crew escape system for its crew capsule in an emergency pad abort situation. The test will last about 220 seconds, beginning during a two-hour window that opens at 06:00 local time (00:30 UTC). However, by the end of the window on Thursday, there was no reports of the test taking place.

While the Indian Space Research Organisation (#ISRO) has not made manned space missions one of their highest priorities, the agency has been quietly proceeding with work on a capsule that would launch atop the #GSLV Mk.III rocket and carry a crew of two into orbit.

The project’s most high-profile test came three and a half years ago, when the Crew Module Atmospheric Reentry Experiment (#CARE) successfully demonstrated that the spacecraft could withstand the rigors of atmospheric reentry.
Source:nasaspaceflight.com

In an epic Indian discovery, a team from the Physical Research Laboratory, #Ahmedabad, has spotted for the first time a distant planet six times bigger than Earth and revolving around a Sun-like star about 600 light years away. Both the planet and the star have been named EPIC. "With this discovery India has joined a handful of countries which have discovered planets around stars," #PRL's parent Indian Space Research Organisation has announced. Significantly, the discovery was made using a #PRL-designed spectrograph, PARAS, to measure and confirm the mass of the new planet.

#EPIC #211945201b (or K2-236b) is the name given to the planet by the discovery team led by PRL's Abhijit Chakraborty. The host star is named #EPIC 211945201 or #K2-236.
Source:The Hindu

Speaking to TOI, #Ahmedabad-based Space Applications Centre (SAC) director Tapan Misra said, “The one-year phase-1 trial of the satellite-based early warning system is over. Its performance has been satisfactory.”
Under a pilot project, the railways had last year installed Isro-developed integrated circuit (IC) chips on some train engines. The Indian Regional Navigation Satellite System (or NaVIC) was used to caution road users at unmanned crossings about approaching trains through hooters installed at these crossings. Explaining its functions, Misra said, “A hooter gets activated as soon as it gets signal from the IC chip installed on a train when its engine is at a distance of 500 metres to 4 km from the crossing. The hooter, linked to the navigation system, thus warns road users about the approaching train. It becomes louder as the train approaches the crossing and goes silent after the train has passed.”
Source:TOI

#Work #hard #silently and let success make the noise. If you have the passion to achieve your goal, then no one can stop you, said scientist Chunaram Dhatarwal from Barmer, who has been selected in ISRO. Dhatarwal was given a warm welcome when he reached Veer Tejaji Hostel at Balotara in Barmer district on Monday. He addressed the students and gave them tips to achieve success. He was welcomed by various voluntary organisations. A resident of Baytu near Pakistan border in Barmer district, Dhatarwal scored 12th rank at all India level in ISRO exam. During school days, Dhatarwal would walk four kilometres bare feet from his village to school. Our house had no light so he would study in the light of chimney, said his father Bholaram.In #Barmer and Jaisalmer, the temperature during summers goes up to 50 degrees and it is very difficult to walk on sand. Our financial condition was very weak due to which my elder son Kishan Kumar could not study and started working in a factory from young age. However, Dhatarwal was determined to study even under such tough circumstances. He wanted to become a scientist since childhood. ISRO Central recruitment board, 2017, had organised an exam for 35 posts and Dhatarwal achieved 12th rank at all India level. Who says you cannot make hole in the sky, just throw a stone, Dhatarwal said, who has followed this principle in life. His farmer father studied till Class VIII, and his mother Ramu Devi is a homemaker, who is illiterate. Till Class VIII, Dhatarwal went to government middle school 4km away from his village. Later, he joined Navodaya School at Pachpadra. He got top rank in Class XII and won gold medal. His elder brother quit his studies and started working in a factory to support the family and continue Dhatarwal’s studies. Even today, there is no electricity in his village. The first place in ISRO exam was bagged by Sunder Sharma and second position by Kanwaljot Singh Sandhu. Dhatarwal gave the credit of his success to his parents and elder brother. Apart from them, teacher Chimnaram Jani guided him which helped him choose this route.Moreover, Dr Abdul #Kalam has been his idol and he is eager to follow his principles. Source:TOI

At 56 years of age, having never experienced a snowfall before, yet lugging kilos of equipment across an icy landscape, Mangala Mani, Isro’s first woman scientist who spent over 403 days in Antarctica, is a true embodiment of ‘Nari Shakti’. Staying in the world’s coldest place where minimum temperatures can slide to -90 degrees Celsius, Mangala Mani was part of a 23-member expedition team that went to India’s research station, Bharati, in the icy continent in November 2016. She was the only woman in the all-men team. In an exclusive interview to TOI, Mani, who successfully completed her mission last December, said, “The Antarctica mission was really a challenge. Climate there was very harsh. We were very careful while going out of our climate-controlled research station. One had to wear polar clothing. Even 2 or 3 hours out in severe cold was too much and one had to come back immediately for warm-up.” When stationed at Bharati during the polar wintering, she was not only the solitary woman in the Indian expedition team but the only female in that zone as the Russian and Chinese earth stations also did not have any woman during the 2016-17 period. 
Source:TOI
#mangalamani #woman #firstindian #antarctica #isro 🚀🛰

Making an effort to extend space research, the Indian Space Research Organisation (ISRO), has started working on building igloo-like habitats on the lunar surface for potential future missions, according to a report by The Times of India.
The moon is a crucial and close destination for research and planetary exploration not just for ISRO but many of the world’s national and international space agencies (such as NASA, ESA, and others). Lunar missions are the first steps in expanding the manned and unmanned exploration of our solar system.
The moon can be used as a laboratory with lower gravity (1/6 of the earth’s gravity field) as it is the closest and most accessible planetary object from Earth.With that in mind, the space research organisation has planned to build ‘lunar habitats,’ which will serve as an “outpost” by sending robots and 3D printers to the Moon. It will be built by using the soil there, as well as other materials.
M Annadurai, Director, ISRO Satellite Centre (ISAC) told the TOI, “We are planning to use the Moon as an outpost—like missions in Antarctica. In the long run, the space station is likely to be scrapped. Many countries, including the US, are considering building more permanent structures on the Moon and working out of there. When that happens, we want India to have contributed.”
#isro #moon #igloos

Indian Space Research Organisation (ISRO) Chairman AS Kiran Kumar has said that the next step in terms of Mars exploration would be to look for alien life or signs of life. He also said that the resources that could support human habitation need to be investigated.
On future of Mars exploration, he said, "The next step would be to search for signs of life and investigate resources that could support human habitation."
"We need to develop capabilities by solving problems going into deep space also. We need to remain relevant and need to solve issues differently. The world is changing very fast and private entrepreneurs are entering the segment," he said.
Kumar was speaking at an inaugural talk at Physical Research Laboratory (PRL) on Wednesday.
He said that ISRO is currently in the process to build reusable launch vehicles. He also said that new technologies for interplanetary missions is also in the works.
Kumar said that this has been done in an effort to reduce the cost incurred in the launch of vehicles.
"We are also on the lookout for equipping with capabilities to carry objects in multiple launches than single launches. We want to reduce cost of access and hence are building reusable launch vehicles," Kumar said.
A three-day brainstorming session on 'Vision and Explorations for Planetary Sciences in Decades 2020-2060' has been organised by PRL to provide a forum for planetary researchers and academicians. They can discuss, explore and present the latest trends, promote understanding and exchange results and opinions in the area of planetary sciences and explorations.
Many newer institutions are setting up an astronomy department in their institutes. One of the IITs has even roped in NASA scientists for their astronomy department. 
What is Reusable Launch Vehicle? 
A reusable launch vehicle or #RLV is a launch system intended to allow for recovery of all or part of its components for later reuse. This contrasts with expendable launch systems, where each launch vehicle is launched once and then discarded. To date, no 100 per cent reusable orbital launch system has ever been created.
Source:newsnation.in

A team of 16 scientists from Satish Dhawan Space Centre (SDSC) SHAR, Sri Harikota, Indian Space Research Organisation is all set to conduct a two-day event at Dr. L. Bullayya College from Sunday.
Contests, space exhibition, science fair and quiz competition, among others form a part of the two-day programme organised as a part of the World Space Week.
Addressing the media on Saturday, deputy general manager of the Second Launch Pad of SDSC G. Surya Narayana said models of rockets including #SLV-3, #ASLV, #PSLV and #GSLV Mk-III along with a few satellite models such as #Aryabhata will be displayed on the college campus.
“Last year, #ISRO conducted similar event in 15 venues in three States. Owing to overwhelming response we are hosting the event in 22 venues spread across Andhra Pradesh, Telangana, Tamil Nadu, Puducherry and Odisha. The idea is to bring a chunk of space technology and #encourage students to take up research in the field,” he stated.
Secretary and correspondent of Dr. L. #Bullayya College G. Madhu Kumar said that ISRO has been scaling new heights and the platform offers a chance for students to look into the opportunities available in the stream.
In the evening, ‘Walk for Space’ rally was flagged off by DCP (Law and Order) K. Fakeerappa. Along with scientists from ISRO, students and college staff took part in the walk taken out from the college premises to Siripurum.

After suffering a #setback because of the unsuccessful launch of its #navigation satellite #IRNSS-1H on August 31, Indian Space Research Organisation (Isro) will resume satellite launches by December.
The space agency will schedule its next launch mission after a fact-finding committee, appointed to find the exact cause of the glitch in the heat separation mechanism of #PSLV C39 rocket that carried navigation satellite IRNSS-1H, submits its report “soon”.
Isro chairman #ASKiran Kumar said, “We will resume launches by November or December.”
Echoing the chairman, Dr K Sivan, director of #Thiruvananthapuram-based Vikram Sarabhai Space Centre (#VSSC) told #TOI, “We will launch either #Cartosat-2 series remote sensing #satellite or the replacement satellite #IRNSS-1I by November or December. We are yet to finalise which of the two satellites will be launched first.”
Source:EconomicTimes

The PSLV-C39 rocket, which failed to launch the #IRNSS 1H satellite on Thursday, was dragged down by at least one tonne of extra weight from the unseparated heat shield after the second stage, its velocity reduced by one kilometre per second.
This greatly reduced the altitude it was to reach for a successful mission, say scientists privy to the project.
Former Isro Satellite Centre director SK Shivakumar said: “The launch vehicle was carrying at least one tonne more than its design permitted it, as the heat shield did not separate. This affected its velocity. For example, it should have attained a velocity of 9.5km per second at the end of it but attained only 8.5km per second.”
Source: EconomicTimes

Last question's answer: Sulphur.
Explanation: Sulphur has a specific gravity of 2. That means if you were to weigh a 2kg lump of Sulphur under water (i.e. WET) it would have an apparent weight of only 1kg. All things weigh more when they burn (oxygen gets added). Sulphur has an atomic number of 16. If it combines with oxygen (atomic number 8) on a one-to-one basis, it will weigh 1 1/2 times as much, That means 2kg will weigh 3kg.

Photo by @JeffMauritzen and words by Justin Kavanagh | Nobody knows when reindeer came to Svalbard. Nobody knows how long ago this hardy beast adapted to the high Arctic by donning a whiter pelt and morphing into the sub-species known as the Svalbard reindeer. Were these stocky, bovine-looking creatures introduced by Swedish trappers as a food source? All we know was that by 1925 they’d been hunted to near extinction. But mankind wised up, passed smarter laws, and Svalbard’s are now among the most protected reindeer in Europe: The archipelago embraces seven of Norway’s 47 national parks. The migrant Samí people hunted reindeer for centuries before they decided to herd them, feed them, and practice sustainable farming long before city scientists came up with the term. The Samí and their reindeer crossed the borders of Norway, Sweden and Finland, in search of lichen to feed the herd. The remains of many ancient reindeer traps still dot these northern landscapes. While no borders stop the migration of Arctic animals, we bipeds had our passports inspected in Tromsø on our way north. If you’re a reindeer of course, no passport required. #Svalbard #reindeer #Norway #arctic

Photo by @andrea_frazzetta | The Sule Pagoda of Yangon, Myanmar. Here a group of teenagers rustles up a night game of soccer in the streets of the city center. A nation long shrouded in mystery, Myanmar has only recently emerged from decades of isolation. Gilded stupas, stepped temples, and candlelit monasteries dot the landscape, revealing a long spiritual tradition that dates back to the first century C.E. To see more photos from my travels, follow me, @andrea_frazzetta. #myanmar #burma #asia

Photo by Gerd Ludwig @gerdludwig | In 1930, Great Smoky Mountains National Park became one of the largest protected areas of the eastern United States. Spanning the borders of North Carolina and Tennessee, it encompasses roughly 525,000 acres of lush landscapes (more tree species than in all of northern Europe), abundant wildlife (65 mammal and 230 bird species), and spectacular scenic beauty.

Photo by @amivitale | Clouds are reflected in the early morning hours at Swan Lake, near Glacier National Park (@glaciernps). The park itself boasts over 700 lakes (only 130 of them are named) and their water can be considered the headwater for the entire continent of North America. From Glacier National Park 's Triple Divide Peak, water can reach the Atlantic, Pacific and Hudson Bay Watersheds. Follow me, @amivitale, for more photos of the wonders of nature around the world.

Photo by @BabakTafreshi | A weasel stands next to a tree trunk in the Alborz Mountains. There are about 200 mammal species in Iran, ranging from whales, dugongs, and dolphins in the Persian Gulf to bears and leopards in the mountains. The wildlife of the country is largely unknown to the world, but most tourists are exploring the cultural and archeological wonders of ancient Persia. #iranwildlife #weasel #alborzmountains

Photo by @drewtrush Drew Rush |  D-Rob and Dan enjoy an evening of flying at Curtis Canyon, Wyoming. The wind in the valley can make for ideal flying conditions for paragliding. For more images from this part of the world, follow along with me, @drewtrush.

Photo by @kevinfaingnaert | The walls around Cartagena, Colombia, were built by the Spanish after Sir Francis Drake and other pirates raided the city for Inca gold. The historic center is surrounded by seven miles of these imposing stone walls, complemented by fortifications and bastions, from which you can watch the sunset over the Caribbean Sea.
Photo by @kahliaprilphoto | Watching a storm roll roll into view over turquoise lakes. There's no place like Lake O'Hara in British Columbia, Canada.

A jaguar paces in tall grass at the Jaguar Reintroduction Center in the Esteros del Iberá, Corrientes Province in northeastern Argentina. The first two jaguars born in this vast wetlands in over seventy-five years mark their first birthday this month. They were born at the Center that is run by Conservation Land Trust Argentina (CLTA), the Argentine team of Tompkins Conservation, in the middle of the brand new Iberá National Park. The young jaguars will one day roam wild and free in Iberá, and that day will mark the return of the top predator to the ecosystem.  Jaguar reintroduction is only one aspect of a long term “re-wilding” project initiative in the region—CLTA is working to restore all the original species to Iberá and are also working with local communities to build a new, sustainable economy based around wildlife tourism.  For more photos of this unique & wild part of the world, follow me, @bethjwald #parqueiberacorrientes #rewilding #yaguarate #jaguar

Photo by Gabriele Galimberti @gabrielegalimbertiphoto and Paolo Woods @paolowoods | A man and his bride-to-be pose for their pre-wedding photos in front of the Marina Bay Sands Hotel in Singapore, host to one of the world’s biggest casinos. Pre-wedding photo shoots are common for people in this part of the world. #singapore #wedding

Photo by @max.lowe | There are many cities on the edge of the sea, but none that I have visited embrace a relationship with the ocean and the life from quite as much as Honolulu. Looking back over diamond head, surfers ride a rising swell, canoes skip across the azure waters of Waikiki, and the setting sun pours over the green mountains of Oahu. It's easy to see quite tangibly the romance imbued in this magical string of volcanic islands. To see more from my time in Hawaii, follow me, @max.lowe.

Photo by @sofia_jaramillo5 | An Uro man paddles a boat on Lake Titicaca in Peru. The Uros live on floating reed islands on Lake Titicaca. They use totora reeds, which grow along the edges of the lake, to make their homes, boats and the islands they live on. For more photos of Peru, follow me, @sofia_jaramillo5. #peru

Photo by @andrea_frazzetta | Dallol is the "Hill of the Spirits" for the Afar Nomads. It's a land of geysers, crystal formations, and sulphurous springs. Dallol is located in Ethiopia, in the Danakil Depression, a remote area subject to the highest average temperatures on the planet. The term Dallol was coined by the Afar people and means dissolution or disintegration, describing a landscape made up of acid ponds. To see more photos from my travels, follow me, @andrea_frazzetta #Danakil #Ethiopia #Africa #Dallol

Photo by @daisygilardini | By April, the pack ice in the frozen fjords of Svalbard are slowing opening up. This young bear is scouting the ice edge, looking for seals. Of the eight species of bears, polar bears are the only bear to be truly carnivorous. They are at the top of the Arctic food chain, and seals represent 90% of their diet. As apex predators, polar bears are exposed to high levels of pollutants, which accumulate in the food chain. Therefore, they’re a good indicator of the health of the entire Arctic ecosystem. Follow me, @daisygilardini, for more images and behind-the-scenes stories. #polarbear #arctic #packice #Svalbard #climatechange

Photo by Muhammed Muheisen @mmuheisen | People enjoy a boat ride on a canal in Amsterdam, Netherlands. For more photos and videos from different parts of the world, follow me, @mmuheisen and @mmuheisenpublic #Amsterdam #netherlands

Photo by Gerd Ludwig @gerdludwig | Happy Independence Day! Designed by the French sculptor F.A. Bartholdi and built by French architect Gustave Eiffel, the Statue of Liberty was a gift from France to the United States. It became an icon of freedom, a symbol of hope, and a welcoming sight to millions of immigrants who arrived by ship from abroad. #IndependenceDay #July4th #StatueofLiberty #NewYork

Photo by @jessicasample | Just a quick ferry ride away from Naples or Capri lies the understated island of Ischia. There you’ll find the pedestrian-only village of Sant’Angelo. Park or take a bus until the road ends and then walk through the quaint bougainvillea-filled town that is bookended by a peninsula where you can climb up and around. #ischia

Photo by @michaelclarkphoto | The Shwedagon Pagoda in central Yangon, Myanmar was originally built in 588 B.C. and expanded in 1774. It now sits 99 meters tall. This image is just a detail shot of the many smaller pagodas at the base of the larger complex. #shwedagonpagoda #yangon #myanmar

Photo by @bertiegregory | A female harbor seal and her pup rest on a rocky outcrop at low tide on the west coast of Vancouver Island in British Columbia, Canada. This place is home to an incredible ecosystem, although much of the coast’s old growth rainforest has been lost to logging. Protecting the forest that's left saves both the homes of countless creatures and the fresh air that we take for granted. #britishcolumbia #photography #wildlife #coast #seal

Photograph by @PaulNicklen | A lone chinstrap penguin catches a ride on a recently overturned iceberg in Antarctica. The grooves in the iceberg are formed by bubbles and currents that shape the massive chunk of ice through time. Follow me, @PaulNicklen, to see my favorite images from the polar regions.

Photo by Gabriele Galimberti @gabrielegalimbertiphoto and Paolo Woods @paolowoods | The construction of a new skyscraper is underway in the Punta Pacifica neighborhood of Panama City. The capital is experiencing a boom of construction, which has left its skyline unrecognizable after just a few years.  #panama #panamacity

Photo by George Steinmetz @geosteinmetz | A pristine beach on the west coast of Isla Magdalena, on the Pacific side of Baja Californa. Isla Magdalena, along with Isla Santa Margarita, protect Magdalena Bay from harsh Pacific winds, allowing for an inviting environment for gray whales and other marine life. There is a small fishing village on this island and no cars, no roads, and no electricity. To explore more of our world from above, follow me, @geosteinmetz.

Photo by @max.lowe I A gaucho wheels his buckskin stallion amid the desolate rocky slopes and moraines of the high chilean Andes. Human partnership with animals is rooted incredibly deep in our ethos and it continues to amaze me as I travel the world. From Montana to Mongolia to Chile, I see the different relationships humans have fostered with horses, as well as how we communally maintain the art from that was born from the ancient advantage of taking to their backs.

Photo by @mborowick | Winter is one of the best times to go ice cave exploring in Iceland. The season is rather short, though— they're only open for those few months before they become too dangerous during the spring and summer seasons. Caves like this one are formed when meltwater flows down a glacier, carving out a network of tunnels in the freeze. The chance to hike one these incredible places can be a once in a lifetime adventure. #icecave #iceland #nature #nordic #explore

A caimen, or yacaré, takes in the sunset in the Esteros del Iberá, a vast grass and marsh region in northern Argentina that is a refuge for an astounding number of birds and animals. In Iberá, alliances between national and provincial governments and the non-profit Conservation Land Trust Argentina have resulted in the creation of the Great Iberá Park just last year.  Work is ongoing to restore all the original wildlife, including those that are extinct or critically endangered in Argentina. The hope is that wildlife tourism will provide a new, sustainable economy for the region. It is an incredible new destination for those interested in wildlife, traditional culture, and vast horizons. For more photos of this unique & wild part of the world, follow me, @bethjwald.  #parqueiberacorrientes #rewilding #esterosdelibera
Photo by @dina_litovsky | Guards change on the hour in front of the National Chiang Kai-Shek Memorial Hall in Taipei, Taiwan. For more images from around the world, follow me, @dina_litovsky.

Photo by @andrea_frazzetta | A group of giraffes are silhouetted in the golden light of the sunset in South Africa's Kruger Park. The giraffe is the tallest terrestrial mammal in the world. The males stand about 5m tall—as high as a single-story house—and the females are just a little shorter.
Giraffes are gentle and timid animals that live in loose social groups. The giraffe's long neck enables it to browse on the leaves of trees. Thus, it does not need to compete with other leaf-eaters feeding lower down. Giraffes eat leaves of many kinds of trees, but acacia trees are their favorites.
The Kruger National Park is one of the largest game reserves in Africa. It covers an area of 19,485 square kilometres (7,523 sq miles) in the provinces of Limpopo and Mpumalanga in northeastern South Africa. To see more photos from my travels, follow me, @andrea_frazzetta. #southafrica #kruger #giraffe

Photo by Simon Norfolk @simonnorfolkstudio I The Kersten Glacier margin, just below Uhuru Peak, with Mount Meru in the distance, photographed whilst climbing Mount Kilimanjaro, Tanzania. Despite continuing shrinkage of Kilimanjaro's glaciers, the steep margins of the Kersten Glacier remain impressive—the cliff is approximately 18 m. (60 ft.) high. The dust bands in the ice absorb more solar radiation than the surrounding, relatively-clean ice, and absorbed energy leads to melting and sublimation. Such stratigraphy is testimony to the complex ice history on Kilimanjaro. Follow me, @simonnorfolkstudiofor, for updates, outtakes, and unpublished and archive material on this and future projects. #photojournalism #Kilimanjaro #climatechange #glaciers

Photo by @michaelclarkphoto | Savannah Cummins climbs a route named "Go Sparky Go"  in Indian Creek, Utah. We used a strobe (i.e. a big flash) to light her up on the climb, which took hours to organize and get up on the wall. #rockclimbing #indiancreek

Photo by @sofia_jaramillo5 | A rainbow illuminates the countryside outside of Manizales, Colombia. Manizales is known as "The City of Open Doors" for its welcoming residents. It sits in the heart of the Colombian Coffee Region and offers a plethora of day trip activities in and around the city. Within a few hours drive, you can visit coffee farms, volcanic hot springs and high altitude national parks. For more photos from Colombia and South America, follow me, @Sofia_Jaramillo5. #colombia #travel
